I run a full UniFi stack at home: gateway, switches, APs, and a set of Protect cameras covering the property. Unifi is my goto brand when it comes to networking and security. Yes it's expensive but the convenience of a product that just works is worth it if you ask me. Before picking up the UTR, my mobile networking setup was already solid and secure: I have dedicated WireGuard connections on every mobile device in my household, auto-connecting based on SSID identification. It worked fine. The UTR isn't a fix for a broken setup. It's an elimination of the friction of having to connect to public W-Fi on multiple devices.

## The Old Way Was Fine. This Is Better.

Per-device WireGuard with SSID-based auto-connect is a legitimate solution. But it has
a consistent pain point: public Wi-Fi captive portals. Every device needs to hit the
portal individually before the tunnel can come up. Three, four, five devices means three,
four, five captive portal interactions, on whatever hostile hotel login page is in front
of you, before you're actually online and tunneled.

The UTR collapses that entirely. One device connects to the hotel Wi-Fi, one captive
portal interaction via the UniFi app, WireGuard tunnel comes up on the router. Every
device behind it is online and tunneled immediately. No per-device portal dance, no
waiting for auto-connect to kick in on each one. The cameras stay in the picture the
same way they did before. I access Protect directly via the app, doorbell alerts work
as expected, and the tunnel means that access runs over my own network path rather than
purely through Ubiquiti's cloud relay.

## First Real-World Use: Barcelona

I pre-loaded the WireGuard profile onto the UTR before leaving. Do this at home while
you have a sane environment to test against. At the hotel, I connected the UTR to the
room's Wi-Fi in client mode. First attempt didn't work. The UTR defaulted to Teleport
rather than my WireGuard config. Quick fix in the app to explicitly set WireGuard as the
active tunnel, second attempt was clean. All devices up, traffic routing home, Protect
accessible, doorbell working.

Worth knowing: if Teleport is enabled on your UniFi account, the UTR reaches for it first.
If you're running your own WireGuard server, explicitly set it as the active VPN in the
app before your trip. Not in the hotel room with five devices waiting on you.

## Hardware

The UTR is small enough to sit in a jacket pocket alongside a passport and runs on just
5W, so any USB port works including the bedside charger in a budget hotel. You get two
USB-C ports (power and tethering, separate) and two GbE RJ45 ports for WAN and LAN.
The polycarbonate case does get warm under load, which is worth knowing if it's sitting
on a nightstand. The radio stack is Wi-Fi 5, which is a dated spec, but in practice the
bottleneck on hotel uplinks is never the UTR's radios. No battery, no SIM, no Wi-Fi 6.
For hotels and Airbnbs with power and an uplink source, none of that matters.

## Bottom Line

The UTR doesn't replace a working travel setup. It streamlines it. Pre-load your
WireGuard profile at home, explicitly set it as the active VPN if you have Teleport
on your account, and from that point forward it's one captive portal interaction for
every device you're carrying. Clean $79 fix for a real friction point.
